class="header_wrapper"><div class="container"><div class="header"><div class="header__logo"></div><div></div></div></div></header><!-- /.header --><!-- /.body-bg --><div class="PostContainer container"><div class="PostContainer__content"><h1 class="title center" style="font-size:1.7em;margin-bottom: 70px;">The 1000 most common Dutch words [Complete List]</h1><p>We produced this list of the thousand most common Dutch words by analyzing an extensive collection of Dutch-language texts including news articles and other articles from the internet.</p>  <p>We used a method called lemmatization to convert the vocabulary words to their canonical (dictionary) form. Lemmatization is a technique that involves grouping the inflected forms of a word so they can treated as a single item.</p><p>This list is intended for language learners who want to focus on mastering the most frequently used words in Dutch.</p><div class="button-panel-wrapper"><div class="button-panel-label">Filter by word type</div><div class="button-panel"><button class="filter-btn pressed-btn" id="show-all">all</button><button class="filter-btn" id="show-nouns">nouns</button><button class="filter-btn" id="show-adjectives">adjectives</button><button class="filter-btn" id="show-verbs">verbs</button><button class="filter-btn" id="show-adverbs">adverbs</button><button class="filter-btn" id="show-pronouns">pronouns</button><button class="filter-btn" id="show-conjunctions">conjunctions</button><button class="filter-btn" id="show-prepositions">prepositions</button></div></div><div class="toggle-comments-div" ><input type="checkbox" id="idWordCommentsCheckbox" name="WordCommentsCheckbox" onclick="toggleWordComments()" autocomplete="off" checked><label for="idWordCommentsCheckbox" style="font-size: 0.8em;"> Show comments for some of the words</label></div><ol id="main-list"><li class="article"><div class="vocab">de</div><div class="pos">[article]</div><div class="definition">(the)</div><p>The Dutch language has two grammatical genders: common and neuter. The definite article “de” is for nouns that have the common gender, while “het” is used for nouns that have the neuter grammatical gender.</p></li><li class="article"><div class="vocab">het</div><div class="pos">[article]</div><div class="definition">(the)</div></li><li class="verb"><div class="vocab">zijn</div><div class="pos">[verb]</div><div class="definition">(to be)</div><p>"Zijn" is an irregular verb, meaning it does not follow the regular conjugation patterns of most Dutch verbs.  It also has many uses, including that of an auxiliary verb, to form compound tenses, such as in the phrase "Ik ben gekomen" (I have come).</p></li><li class="preposition"><div class="vocab">van</div><div class="pos">[preposition]</div><div class="definition">(from)</div><p>Another reason why this is such a common Dutch word is that it often appears in Dutch names, for example “van Gogh”.</p></li><li class="article"><div class="vocab">een</div><div class="pos">[article]</div><div class="definition">(a)</div><p>This is the indefinite article in Dutch. It stays the same regardless of the grammatical gender of the corresponding noun.</p></li><li class="conjunction"><div class="vocab">en</div><div class="pos">[conjunction]</div><div class="definition">(and)</div><p>In Dutch, as in most languages, the most common words are generally short.  This linguistic phenomenon is called the “brevity law” or “Zipf's law of abbreviation”.</p></li><li class="preposition"><div class="vocab">in</div><div class="pos">[preposition]</div><div class="definition">(in)</div></li><li class="preposition"><div class="vocab">op</div><div class="pos">[preposition]</div><div class="definition">(on)</div></li><li class="preposition"><div class="vocab">te</div><div class="pos">[preposition]</div><div class="definition"></div></li><li class="preposition"><div class="vocab">met</div><div class="pos">[preposition]</div><div
